Great question. A brittle test is one that breaks with minor changes in the input, like your `from_str_into_string` case above. If you change the data slightly to include whitespace, it still passes. But a good test should use property-based testing or at least have an explicit assertion on error boundaries. Like this: 

```rust
proptest::proptest!(
    proptest_fn(|input: Vec<u8|> {
        let s = String::from_utf8_lossy(&input);
        assert!(s.is_ok());
    })
)
```
Or better yet, for your specific case: 

```rust
proptest::proptest!(
    proptest_fn(|data: &[u8]| {
        let s = String::from_utf8_lossy(data);
        assert_eq!(s.to_string(), "Valid UTF-8");
        assert_eq!(s.len(), 5); // The actual length
    })
)
```
This forces the function to validate its input, not just handle it gracefully.
